text: Movie vs reality:  *Movie:*  Barry Seal is an airline pilot who looks like Tom Cruise recruited by the CIA to smuggle drugs and weapons as part of the Iran Contra Affair.  *Reality:*  Barry Seal is an airline pilot who likes like Alex Jones.  He gets fired by TWA after 8 years and starts running drugs for the Medellin Cartel.  After being arrested and convicted in 1984, Seal approached the DEA and offered to become an informant.  He smuggled drugs a few times in order to get information about the Sandinistas.   His 10 year conviction was converted to public service at the Salvation Army.  In 1986, he was assassinated by Colombian assassins hired by the Medellin Cartel.  Any involvement with Iran Contra was probably tangental at best.

text: Elements of Iran Contra get the big screen treatment.  Seal was no joke.  He was a major, major supplier, courier if you will, of coke that was processed into crack.  Seal was in the right place at the right time, same with Freeway Ricky Ross.  They both made serious money off the crack trade that was just starting to get rolling in the early 1980s in major cities across the country that were beginning to feel the sting of deindustrialization and the impending low-wage, underemployment economy. Mena Arkansas was a frequent drug drop site, I presume the movie will touch on this.  The drugs, tons of cash and gun running that Seal and some others (there were others) were hauling was basically controlled by elements of the CIA to get around the Boland Amendment.  During the 1970s and early 1980s indigenous-populist movements in Central America were gaining power by serving the people.  For decades El Salvador and Nicaragua were lorded over by corrupt and violent kleptocrats.  By the late 1970s populist movements fighting for economic justice were starting to gain ground.  The Washington imperialists feared these democratic movements like the plague, see, the kleptocrats were always under Washington's thumb; opening their countires up to corporate capitalist penetration.  Since these long over due populist movements sent such fear into the ruling class in Washington, Ollie and the boys along with covert CIA operatives started running the guns to mercenaries to fight the guerrillas who were a part of the populist movements.  Anytime the powers that be need to wage a clandestine war (work around the Boland Amendment) they of course need to drum up cash, lots of cash.  That's where Seal and the boyz came in.  I'll be very interested to see how candid this movie is about the role of the national security state imperialists in Washington, sometimes now referred to as the "Deep State."  For further reading on what I've quickly sketched out above: see the works by Gary Webb, Nicholas Shou, Robert Parry, and Cockburn and St. Clair's book 'Whiteout'.  For a deeper understanding of the progressive movements in Central America in the 1970s and early '80s, see the books and articles by James Petras, Michael Parenti and Noam Chomsky.  Also see the dynamite movies "Salvador" by Oliver Stone, and the film "Romero."

text: Elements of Iran Contra get the big screen treatment.    Seal was no joke.  He was a major supplier, courier if you will, of coke that was  processed into crack.  Seal was in the right place at the right time,  same with Freeway Ricky Ross.  They both made serious money off the  crack trade that was just starting to get rolling in the early 1980s in  major cities across the country that were beginning to feel the sting of  deindustrialization and the impending low-wage, underemployment  economy.   Mena Arkansas was a frequent drug drop site, I presume the  movie will touch on this.  The drugs, tons of cash and gun running that  Seal and some others (there were others) were hauling was basically  controlled by elements of the CIA to get around the Boland Amendment. ¬† During the 1970s and early 1980s indigenous-populist movements in  Central America were gaining power by serving the people.  For decades  El Salvador and Nicaragua (and some of the other C. American states) were lorded over by corrupt and violent kleptocrats.  By the mid/late 1970s populist movements fighting for economic justice were starting to gain ground.  The Washington imperialists  feared these democratic movements like the plague, see, the kleptocrats  were always under Washington's thumb; opening their states up to  corporate capitalist penetration.  Since these long over due populist  movements sent such fear into the ruling class in Washington, Ollie and  the boys along with covert CIA operatives started running guns to  mercenaries to fight the guerrillas who were a part of the populist  movements.  The Contras were some of these mercenaries.  They were directly responsible for some of the most heinous torture and murder of innocent civilians that the Western hemisphere has ever witnessed: castrating children in front of their parents, then cutting off heads of parents in front of children, it's all documented and sickening beyond belief.  American tax dollars were indirectly supporting all this and the US coke market was directly involved in it.  Anytime the powers that be need to wage a clandestine war  (work around the Boland Amendment and domestic public opinion) they of course need to drum up cash, lots of cash.  That's where Seal, the coke and the boyz came in.    I'll be very interested to see how candid this movie is about the role of the  national security state imperialists in Washington, sometimes now  referred to as the "Deep State."    For further reading on what I've quickly sketched out above: see the works by Gary Webb, Nicholas Shou, Robert Parry, and Cockburn and St. Clair's book 'Whiteout'.  For a  deeper understanding of the progressive movements in Central America in  the 1970s and early '80s, see the books and articles by James Petras,  Michael Parenti and Noam Chomsky.  Also see the dynamite movies  "Salvador" by Oliver Stone, and the film "Romero."

text: Ulster Gazette - News - JJ‚Äôs star power wows Hollywood August 16, 2016        Read all here.....    Keady‚Äôs JJ McParland in LA where she has met up with Hollywood movie studio  bosses.BRITAIN'S Got Talent star Jesse Jane McParland is on the verge of  becoming a star of the big screen.   Since the 10 year-old burst unto our screens in the last series of BGT millions of people around the world have witnessed her extraordinary talent.  And now studio bosses in LA are desperate to get JJ signed up to star in the movies. The Keady girl, along with her dad Gary enjoyed an all-expenses-paid trip to La La Land last week to meet with a major Holywood studio. The pair were joined on the trip by JJ's management team of Brooke Kinsella and Brian Gersh and while they are keeping tight-lipped for now it's understood major developments are in  the pipeline very soon. The killers were indicted by a state grand jury on March 27, 1986.[19] In May 1987, Luis Carlos Quintero-Cruz, Miguel Velez (died in custody 2015),[20] and Bernardo Antonio Vasquez were convicted of first degree murder in Seal's death, and sentenced to life in prison without parole.[21]  WIKI
